.TH POWER4CTL 1 "July 2026" "power4ctl 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
power4ctl \- serial management tool for the power4 ESP32 device
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B power4ctl
.RB [ \-p
.IR port ]
.RB [ \-b
.IR baud ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR seconds ]
.RB [ \-v ]
.I command
.RI [ args... ]
.PP
.B power4ctl
.RB [ \-p
.IR port ]
.RB [ \-b
.IR baud ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR seconds ]
.RB [ \-v ]
.B \-D
.RB [ \-i
.IR interval ]
.RB [ \-l
.IR lock\-seconds ]
.RB [ \-o
.IR outdir ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B power4ctl
communicates with a power4 ESP32 device over its serial console.
It opens the port, acquires an exclusive lock, elicits the
.B power4>
prompt, issues a command, and returns the result.
.PP
For the
.BR "json " commands,
the device responds with a framed-JSON line in the form
.PP
.RS
.EX
P4J1 \fIsize\fP \fIsha1hex\fP \fIjson\fP
.EE
.RE
.PP
.B power4ctl
validates the length and SHA-1 checksum before printing the JSON object
to standard output.
Log lines and other console noise from the device are silently ignored.
.PP
Any command not listed below is sent verbatim to the device and all
output lines are echoed to standard output until the
.B power4>
prompt returns.
.PP
In daemon mode
.RB ( \-D ),
.B power4ctl
runs indefinitely, opening the serial port at each interval, collecting
the JSON reports
.RB ( batteries ,
.BR banks ,
.BR relays ,
.BR logs ),
writing them atomically to the output directory, then closing the port
and sleeping until the next interval.
Each file is written to a hidden temporary name and then renamed into
place so readers never see a partial file.
If the port cannot be locked within the lock-wait timeout the cycle is
skipped and the existing files are left unchanged.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-p " port"
Serial port to use.
Default:
.IR /dev/ttyACM0 .
.TP
.BI \-b " baud"
Baud rate.
Default:
.IR 115200 .
.TP
.BI \-t " seconds"
Per-operation timeout: how long to wait for the prompt and for each
command response.
Default:
.IR 2 .
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose mode.
Logs every byte sent
.RB ( >>> )
and received
.RB ( <<< )
to standard error, with non-printable characters shown as
.BR \en ,
.BR \er ,
.BR \et ,
or
.BR \exNN .
.TP
.B \-D
Daemon mode.
Run forever, collecting all three JSON reports on a periodic loop.
Takes no command arguments.
Terminated cleanly by
.B SIGTERM
or
.BR SIGINT .
.TP
.BI \-i " seconds"
Daemon poll interval in seconds.
Default:
.IR 60 .
.TP
.BI \-l " seconds"
How long to wait for the serial port lock before skipping a daemon cycle.
Default:
.IR 5 .
.TP
.BI \-o " dir"
Directory where daemon mode writes
.IR batteries.json ,
.IR banks.json ,
.IR relays.json ,
and
.I logs.json
(created if it does not exist).
Default:
.IR /run/power4 .
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B json batteries
Request the current battery observations from the device and print the
JSON object to standard output.
.TP
.B json banks
Request the current battery bank state from the device and print the
JSON object to standard output.
.TP
.B json logs
Request a snapshot of the device's recent system log text (a rolling 16 KB
buffer) and print the JSON object to standard output.
The log text is in the object's
.B text
field.
.TP
.B json relays
Request the current relay state from the device and print the JSON object
to standard output.
.TP
.BI "stage " filename
Read
.I filename
from disk, compute its SHA-1, and upload it to the device as a staged
policy program.
The file is sent base64-encoded in 76-character lines preceded by a
.B "policy upload \fIsha1hex\fP"
command.
A blank line signals end of upload.
On success, the device's confirmation message is printed to standard output.
.TP
.I anything-else
The command is sent verbatim to the device and all response lines are
echoed to standard output until the
.B power4>
prompt returns.
This provides full access to the device's console without a separate
terminal emulator.
.SH DAEMON OUTPUT FILES
In daemon mode, four files are maintained under the output directory
(default
.IR /run/power4 ):
.TP
.I batteries.json
Current battery observations.
.TP
.I banks.json
Current battery bank state.
.TP
.I relays.json
Current relay state.
.TP
.I logs.json
Snapshot of the device's recent system log text (rolling 16 KB buffer).
.PP
Each file is written atomically: new content is first written to
.RI .tmp. name .json
in the same directory, then renamed into place.
If a cycle fails (port busy, timeout), the previous files are not modified.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
The command completed successfully (or daemon mode was terminated by signal).
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (device busy, timeout, checksum mismatch, upload
failure, etc.).
A message is printed to standard error.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /dev/ttyACM0
Default serial port (USB CDC ACM, used by the ESP32 USB-JTAG/Serial interface).
.TP
.I /run/power4/
Default daemon output directory.
.SH LOCKING
.B power4ctl
calls
.BR flock (2)
with
.B LOCK_EX|LOCK_NB
and sets
.B TIOCEXCL
on the port immediately after opening it.
In single-shot mode, if another process already holds the port the tool
exits immediately with an error rather than waiting.
In daemon mode, the lock attempt is retried every 500\ ms for up to
.I lock\-seconds
seconds (default\ 5) before the cycle is skipped.
.SH NOTES
The port is configured in raw 8N1 mode with the requested baud rate and
no hardware flow control.
For USB CDC ACM devices the baud rate setting is advisory and the
device may ignore it.
.PP
The prompt is elicited by sending a carriage return and waiting for
.BR "power4> " .
Up to three attempts are made, sharing the timeout evenly.
.PP
SHA-1 verification uses a self-contained FIPS\~180-4 implementation with
no external library dependency.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR picocom (1),
.BR esptool (1),
.BR flock (2),
.BR termios (3)
.SH AUTHOR
Jim Studt <jim@studt.net>
